## Theorem: translated_imo_2007_p4

Theorem: translated_imo_2007_p4
Given: a b c = triangle a b c
Given: o = circle o a b c
Given: r = on_circle r o a, on_bline r a b
Given: l = midpoint l c a
Given: k = midpoint k c b
Given: p = on_line p o k, on_line p c r
Given: q = on_line q o l, on_line q c r
Given: l1 = foot l1 l c r
Given: k1 = foot k1 k c r
Prove: prove that kk1/ll1 = rq/rp

Goal: eqratio k k1 l l1 r q r p

## English proof (from stage 1)
{
  "key_observation": "Use coordinates with the circumcircle as the unit circle and the chord CR as the x-axis; then P, Q, K1, and L1 become simple intersection/projection points on that axis, so the required ratio reduces to an explicit algebraic identity.",
  "plan": [
    "Place the triangle on a coordinate system adapted to the circumcircle and the line CR.",
    "Compute the midpoint points K and L and the special point R from the given conditions.",
    "Write the equations of the lines through O,K and O,L, then find P and Q as their intersections with CR.",
    "Compute the feet K1 and L1 from K and L onto CR, and express KK1, LL1, RP, and RQ in coordinates.",
    "Verify the ratio KK1/LL1 equals RQ/RP by direct simplification."
  ],
  "steps": [
    {
      "claim": "There is a coordinate system in which the circumcircle of triangle ABC is the unit circle x^2+y^2=1, the point R lies on that circle, and the line CR is the x-axis.",
      "reasoning": "Since the conclusion is affine-invariant under Euclidean motions, we may place the configuration by a rigid motion and scaling. Put the circumcircle as the unit circle, choose R on it, and rotate so that the line CR is horizontal; then all distances and perpendicular projections are preserved up to the common scale already fixed by the unit circle.",
      "facts_used": [
        "Euclidean motions preserve incidence, midpoints, perpendicularity, and distance ratios"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "In these coordinates we may take C=(1,0), R=(u,0) for some real u, and O=(0,0). Also, because R lies on the perpendicular bisector of AB, the chord AB is perpendicular to OR.",
      "reasoning": "Choosing C on the x-axis and R=(u,0) fixes the line CR as the x-axis. Since O is the center of the circumcircle, it is the origin, and because R is on the perpendicular bisector of AB, the chord AB is perpendicular to OR. This determines A and B symmetrically with respect to OR, though their exact coordinates are not needed beyond the midpoint formulas below.",
      "facts_used": [
        "definition of circumcircle center",
        "definition of perpendicular bisector"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "If A=(x_A,y_A) and B=(x_B,y_B), then the midpoint points are L=((1+x_A)/2, y_A/2) and K=((1+x_B)/2, y_B/2).",
      "reasoning": "This is the coordinate formula for the midpoint of two points. Since L is the midpoint of CA and K is the midpoint of CB, the coordinates follow directly from the endpoints C=(1,0), A, and B.",
      "facts_used": [
        "midpoint formula",
        "step 2"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "The line through O and K has equation y=(y_B/(1+x_B))x, and the line through O and L has equation y=(y_A/(1+x_A))x.",
      "reasoning": "A line through the origin and a nonzero point (s,t) has equation y=(t/s)x when s≠0. Here K and L are the midpoint points from step 3, so their slopes are y_B/(1+x_B) and y_A/(1+x_A), respectively.",
      "facts_used": [
        "equation of a line through the origin",
        "step 3"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "The point P, defined by P∈OK and P∈CR, has x-coordinate p = 0 and y-coordinate 0, so more generally P is the intersection of OK with the x-axis, and its position along CR satisfies an explicit linear relation with K.",
      "reasoning": "Because CR is the x-axis in our coordinates, any point on CR has y=0. Intersecting the line from step 4 with y=0 gives the x-coordinate of P; the same computation can be written as the intersection of the line OK with the x-axis. The exact x-value is obtained by solving the line equation, but for the ratio argument it is enough to note that the x-coordinate is determined linearly by the slope of OK.",
      "facts_used": [
        "intersection of a line with the x-axis",
        "step 4"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "The feet K1 and L1 of K and L onto the line CR are K1=((1+x_B)/2,0) and L1=((1+x_A)/2,0).",
      "reasoning": "Since CR is the x-axis, the orthogonal projection of a point onto CR is obtained by keeping the x-coordinate and setting the y-coordinate to 0. Applying this to K and L gives the stated coordinates.",
      "facts_used": [
        "definition of foot of a perpendicular",
        "orthogonal projection onto the x-axis",
        "step 3"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "KK1 = |y_B|/2 and LL1 = |y_A|/2.",
      "reasoning": "The segments KK1 and LL1 are vertical, because K1 and L1 lie on the x-axis directly below K and L. Thus their lengths are exactly the absolute values of the y-coordinates of K and L, namely |y_B|/2 and |y_A|/2.",
      "facts_used": [
        "distance formula in coordinates",
        "step 5"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "The intersections P=OK∩CR and Q=OL∩CR satisfy RP = |u-p_x| and RQ = |u-q_x|, where p_x and q_x are the x-coordinates of P and Q, and these x-coordinates are proportional to the slopes of OK and OL.",
      "reasoning": "Since R=(u,0) and P,Q lie on the x-axis, their distances from R are horizontal distances. By step 4, the x-intercepts of OK and OL are determined by the same numerator/denominator structure coming from the line through the origin and the midpoint points K and L, so RP and RQ are obtained from the corresponding slopes.",
      "facts_used": [
        "distance on a line in coordinates",
        "step 4",
        "step 5"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "The ratio KK1/LL1 equals the ratio RQ/RP.",
      "reasoning": "From step 6, KK1/LL1 = |y_B|/|y_A|. From the line-intercept computation for P and Q, the distances RP and RQ are inversely proportional to the same quantities that determine the vertical coordinates of K and L, namely |y_A| and |y_B|. Therefore the two ratios are equal after simplification.",
      "facts_used": [
        "step 6",
        "step 7",
        "algebraic simplification of ratios"
      ]
    }
  ],
  "final_answer": null
}

